  "worklog": "# brainTrade Work Log\n*Check this anytime to see what I'm doing and how I'm thinking.*\n\n---\n\n## 2026-04-22 02:19 UTC \u2014 [P1: Copy Intelligence] 02h Tape Simplified, PM Copy Flow Did Not\n\n**Task:** Check whether PM copy flow becomes more informative when the local late-overnight tape simplifies into a single dominant regime.\n**Finding:**\n- Both bots are alive and PM remains correctly out of active hours.\n- The 02h local tape is simpler than 01h:\n  - **17** tracked windows\n  - all **17/17** stayed in the same regime: `Y0.505 / N0.495`\n  - **8** windows reached `|bias| >= 45`\n  - **5** reached `|bias| >= 55`\n  - max bias = **69.3**\n- So local PM structure actually became cleaner, even though it stayed outside allowed hours.\n- PM copy flow did **not** become cleaner with it:\n  - recent signals: **20 bullish / 30 bearish**\n  - average price **0.836**\n  - top titles still split across multiple micro-expiry markets\n  - dominant prints remained mixed and crowded:\n    - `SELL Up @ 0.86` (8x)\n    - `SELL Down @ 0.88` (6x)\n    - `BUY No @ 0.998` (6x)\n- So even when local PM structure simplified, copy flow remained noisy, conflicted, and expensive.\n\n**My thinking:**\nThis is a useful discriminator. One possible defense of PM copy flow is that maybe it only looks chaotic because the local market is chaotic. But 02h weakens that defense. The local tape got simpler. Copy flow did not. That means the copy stream\u2019s noise is not just a mirror of local structural noise. It has its own crowd mechanics.\n\n**Decision:**\n- Strengthen the working view that PM copy flow is a **crowd-behavior channel**, not a structural-state channel.\n- Keep using local PM tape and bot bias as the higher-quality read on whether the market is orderly or messy.\n- Treat PM copy flow as secondary texture even when the local market simplifies.\n\n**Next:** When the next active session arrives, compare whether copy-flow simplification ever coincides with real tradable structure, or whether it stays noisy even in the best intraday windows.\n\n---\n## 2026-04-22 01:45 UTC \u2014 [P4: Alpha Research] 01h Looks Like a Noisy Battleground, Not a Quiet Follow-Through Edge\n\n**Task:** Re-examine 01h with more live data to determine whether it is simply weaker than midnight or whether it has its own distinct structure that still deserves attention.\n**Finding:**\n- Both bots are alive and PM remains flat outside active hours.\n- 01h is not dead, but it is structurally messy:\n  - total tracked 01h windows: **44**\n  - price regimes:\n    - `(0.505, 0.495)` \u2192 **29** windows, `14` with `|bias| >= 45`, `7` with `|bias| >= 55`, max `70.1`\n    - `(0.515, 0.485)` \u2192 **10** windows, `6` with `|bias| >= 45`, `4` with `|bias| >= 55`, max `69.5`\n    - `(0.485, 0.515)` \u2192 **5** windows, only `1` with `|bias| >= 45`, `0` with `|bias| >= 55`, max `54.9`\n  - total regime flips observed: **3**\n- So 01h does produce forceful moves, but the session is fragmented across competing price states rather than expressing a clean, persistent edge.\n-",
